\\\\\\\\\\nWhen a `tdf/<key>` PR you opened is merged, `.github/workflows/jira-pr-merged.yml` finalizes things (transitions Jira to Done, deletes the head branch). Do not try to do that yourself.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nYour job on each run:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n1. Read the generated ticket artefacts, especially the spec file referenced by `SPEC_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n2. Write or update the implementation plan at the exact path in `PLAN_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n3. Implement only the requested ticket work on the current branch.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n4. Write the Jira-facing summary or answer to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n5. Keep generated ticket artefacts organised under `spec/<TICKET-ID>/` and avoid cluttering the repository root.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n6. Leave pull request creation, branch pushes, and Jira commenting to the workflow.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Dispatch Flow Context\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nWhen the dispatch flow runs, the workflow exports these env vars before invoking you:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `ISSUE_KEY`, `ISSUE_TITLE`, `JIRA_ISSUE_URL`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `KIND`: `pr` (expects code changes plus a PR) or `answer` (expects only ticket-folder updates and a Jira-facing response)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `IS_NEW`: `true` if this is the first run for the ticket, `false` if continuing\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `LAST_SESSION_ID`: prior Codex session id, when known (currently informational; resume is not auto-wired)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `TICKET_FOLDER` (e.g. `spec/KAN-1`), `STATE_FILE`, `TRANSCRIPT_FILE`, `SPEC_FILE`, `PLAN_FILE`, `RESPONSE_FILE`, `RUN_DIR`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n`KIND` is determined from Jira:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Label `claude:answer` → `answer` (highest priority).\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Label `claude:pr` → `pr`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Issue type `Question` → `answer`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Default → `pr`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n(Label names retain the `claude:` prefix for backward compatibility with Jira automation rules; semantically they map to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"answer mode\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" / \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"PR mode\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" regardless of the underlying agent.)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nIf `KIND=answer`, do not edit any file outside `TICKET_FOLDER`. Write the full answer to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nIf `KIND=pr`, make minimal correct repository changes, update `PLAN_FILE`, and write a short Jira-facing summary to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Operating Context\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The branch name normally starts with a Jira key, often lowercased by Jira automation. The dispatch flow uses `tdf/<ticket-id-lowercase>` for PR mode.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The workflow normalises Jira keys before generating ticket artefact paths.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The current branch is the work branch. Do not switch branches.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Do not merge pull requests, close tickets, or edit Jira directly unless the ticket explicitly asks for that behaviour and the workflow provides the required tools.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Prefer small, direct changes that match the ticket acceptance criteria